1. From the student’s own OS terminal (host) – connect to
VM : 

[root@redhat /root]$ who | grep pts
user     pts/0        2025-11-25 11:06 (192.168.153.1)
user     pts/1        2025-11-25 17:45 (192.168.153.1)
user     pts/2        2025-11-25 17:53 (192.168.153.1)

------------------------------------------------------------
1. create a new group named 'labgroup' on a Linux system

[root@redhat /root]$ groupadd labgroup


Result:

[root@redhat /root]$ grep "^labgroup:" /etc/group
labgroup:x:1001:

------------------------------------------------------------
2. create a new user named 'labuser' with a home directory, default shell '/bin/bash'
[root@redhat /root]$ adduser labuser -s /bin/bash

Result:

[root@redhat /root]$ id labuser
uid=1001(labuser) gid=1003(labuser) groups=1003(labuser)

------------------------------------------------------------
3. add user 'labuser' to primary group 'labgroup'

[root@redhat /root]$ usermod -g labgroup labuser

Result:

[root@redhat /root]$ id labuser
uid=1001(labuser) gid=1001(labgroup) groups=1001(labgroup)

------------------------------------------------------------
4. set the password for the user 'labuser'

[root@redhat /root]$ echo "logadacemy" | passwd labuser --stdin

------------------------------------------------------------
5. add the user 'labuser' to the 'wheel' group (sudo group)

[root@redhat ~]# usermod -aG wheel labuser

Result:
[root@redhat ~]# id labuser
uid=1001(labuser) gid=1001(labgroup) groups=1001(labgroup),10(wheel)


------------------------------------------------------------
6. give 'labuser' explicit sudo rights (with vim/visudo)

[root@redhat /root]$ visudo

Add 'labuser ALL=(ALL)       ALL' to sudoers file.

------------------------------------------------------------
7. switch user to 'labuser'
8. change directory to 'labuser's home directory

[root@redhat /root]$ su labuser
[labuser@redhat /root]$ cd

------------------------------------------------------------
9. Execute the commands that creates a 'lab' directory inside 'labuser's home
directory, change directory into it

[labuser@redhat /home/labuser]$ mkdir ~/lab
[labuser@redhat /home/labuser]$ cd ~/lab

------------------------------------------------------------
10.execute whoami, id, and pwd. redirect their outputs into a file called 'answer'
using redirection operators.

[labuser@redhat lab]$ whoami > answer.txt ; id >> answer.txt ; pwd >> answer.txt
[labuser@redhat lab]$ cat answer.txt
labuser
uid=1001(labuser) gid=1001(labgroup) groups=1001(labgroup) context=unconfined_u:unconfined_r:unconfined_t:s0-s0:c0.c1023
/home/labuser/lab

------------------------------------------------------------
11. Use 'man' to get know about 'cut' command, specially, 'd' and 'f' options. (you can
also research online and look examples)

man cut \-d \-t

------------------------------------------------------------
12.using 'cut' command with 'd' and 'f' options, print last username in /etc/passwd file
, using 'tail' command, to terminal. then append output to 'answer' file.

[labuser@redhat lab]$ tail -1 /etc/passwd | cut -d ":" -f 1 | tee -a answer.txt
labuser

------------------------------------------------------------
13.in one command, use 'grep' to get lines which starting with 'lab' for '/etc/passwd'
and '/etc/group' file, and append output to 'answer' file.

[labuser@redhat lab]$ grep "^lab" /etc/passwd | tee -a answer.txt
labuser:x:1001:1001::/home/labuser:/bin/bash

[root@redhat ~]# grep "^lab" /etc/group | tee -a answer.txt
labgroup:x:1001:
labuser:x:1003:


------------------------------------------------------------
14.use 'man' tool to read manual of 'wget' command.

man wget

------------------------------------------------------------
15.using 'wget' command, download file:
https://raw.githubusercontent.com/elastic/examples/master/Common%20Data%2
0Formats/apache_logs/apache_logs

[labuser@redhat lab]$ mkdir /tmp/logs
[labuser@redhat lab]$ wget -O /tmp/logs/apache.log \
"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/elastic/examples/master/Common%20Data%20Formats/apache_logs/apache_logs"
